The University of Sydney (USyd) holds the 19th position globally in the QS World University Rankings 2025 and ranks 60th in the Times Higher Education (THE) World University Rankings 2025, placing it consistently among the top 1% of universities worldwide. Across 51 subjects evaluated in the QS World University Rankings by Subject 2024, USyd achieved top-50 global rankings in 36 disciplines, with seven subjects entering the global top 20. In the 2023 Excellence in Research for Australia (ERA) assessment, 100% of USyd’s research was rated at or above world standard, with 80% of disciplines receiving the highest rating of 5 (well above world standard). These figures position the university as Australia’s oldest and most comprehensive research institution, founded in 1850, and a primary destination for international students—over 50,000 international enrolments from 170 countries in 2024, according to the Australian Department of Education. For prospective students evaluating global subject performance, USyd’s breadth of excellence across humanities, health sciences, engineering, and business offers distinct pathways aligned with career outcomes.

## **Global Subject Rankings Overview**

The University of Sydney’s subject-level performance is most comprehensively tracked through the **QS World University Rankings by Subject** and the **THE World University Rankings by Subject**. In the 2024 QS subject rankings, USyd ranked in the global top 20 for **Sports-Related Subjects** (4th), **Anatomy & Physiology** (12th), **Veterinary Science** (16th), **Pharmacy & Pharmacology** (18th), **Law & Legal Studies** (19th), **Civil & Structural Engineering** (20th), and **Education & Training** (20th). The university also placed in the top 30 for **Accounting & Finance** (25th), **Medicine** (27th), **Psychology** (29th), and **Architecture & Built Environment** (29th). In the THE World University Rankings by Subject 2024, USyd achieved top-50 positions in **Clinical & Health** (38th), **Life Sciences** (45th), **Social Sciences** (47th), and **Business & Economics** (49th). These subject-level rankings reflect the university’s strategic investment in research-intensive faculties and its strong industry partnerships, particularly in health and law.

### **QS Subject Rankings Methodology**
QS evaluates subjects using five indicators: academic reputation (global survey), employer reputation, research citations per paper, H-index (research productivity and impact), and international research network. For subjects like Medicine and Law, academic reputation carries a 40% weight, while for Engineering disciplines, employer reputation is weighted at 30%. USyd’s consistently high scores across these indicators—particularly in employer reputation for Law (92.3/100) and citations per paper for Life Sciences (89.7/100)—explain its sustained top-20 performance.

## **Health & Medical Sciences**

The University of Sydney’s **Faculty of Medicine and Health** is the largest in Australia, with over 4,000 students and 1,500 research staff. In the QS 2024 subject rankings, **Medicine** placed 27th globally, while **Anatomy & Physiology** ranked 12th and **Pharmacy & Pharmacology** ranked 18th. The university’s **Sydney Medical School** operates across eight clinical schools and 30 teaching hospitals, including Royal Prince Alfred Hospital and Westmead Hospital, providing students with direct clinical exposure from year one. Research output in health sciences is exceptionally strong: USyd published over 6,000 health-related papers in 2023, with a field-weighted citation impact of 1.8, according to SciVal 2024 data. The **Charles Perkins Centre**, a $385 million research hub opened in 2014, focuses on metabolic diseases, obesity, and diabetes, and has produced over 1,200 peer-reviewed publications since its inception.

### **Nursing & Midwifery**
Nursing at USyd ranked 45th globally in QS 2024, with the university offering a two-year Master of Nursing (Graduate Entry) that attracts students from non-nursing undergraduate backgrounds. Clinical placements are integrated across all semesters, with partnerships in over 20 public and private hospitals in New South Wales. The program’s employability rate is 94% within four months of graduation, based on the 2023 Graduate Outcomes Survey.

### **Dentistry**
Dentistry at USyd ranked 36th globally in QS 2024. The Sydney Dental School, established in 1901, treats over 100,000 patients annually through its network of 10 public dental clinics. The Doctor of Dental Medicine (DMD) program requires a prior bachelor’s degree and offers clinical placements from the first semester, with a student-to-clinical-chair ratio of 4:1.

## **Law & Social Sciences**

The **Sydney Law School**, founded in 1855, is Australia’s oldest law school and consistently ranks among the world’s best. In the QS 2024 subject rankings, **Law & Legal Studies** placed 19th globally, with an academic reputation score of 91.5/100 and an employer reputation score of 89.2/100. The law school offers a three-year Juris Doctor (JD) program for students with non-law undergraduate degrees, and a five-year combined Bachelor of Laws (LLB) program. USyd law graduates hold positions at top-tier firms globally—Clayton Utz, Allens, and Herbert Smith Freehills—and 22% of Australian High Court judges are USyd alumni. The **Sydney Centre for International Law** and the **Julian Leeser Centre for Constitutional Law** provide research hubs for international and comparative law.

### **Social Sciences & Politics**
The Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences houses USyd’s **Social Sciences** programs, which ranked 47th globally in THE 2024. The **Department of Government and International Relations** offers a Master of International Relations with specialisations in global governance and security studies. Research output in political science is high: USyd published 420 papers in the field in 2023, with 35% appearing in top-quartile journals, according to Scopus data. The **United States Studies Centre**, established in 2006 with a $25 million endowment, produces policy papers on US-Australia relations and hosts visiting scholars from Harvard and Stanford.

## **Engineering & Technology**

USyd’s **Faculty of Engineering** ranked 40th globally in QS 2024 for Engineering & Technology overall, with **Civil & Structural Engineering** achieving a top-20 position (20th globally). **Electrical & Electronic Engineering** ranked 45th, and **Computer Science & Information Systems** ranked 50th. The faculty houses the **Sydney Nano Institute**, a $150 million interdisciplinary research centre focusing on nanotechnology applications in energy, medicine, and materials science. In the 2023 ERA assessment, 95% of engineering research was rated at or above world standard, with **Materials Engineering** and **Mechanical Engineering** receiving the highest rating of 5. The **School of Computer Science** offers a Master of Data Science and a Master of Cybersecurity, both of which have seen a 40% increase in international enrolments since 2021, reflecting global demand for these skills.

### **Civil Engineering Specialisations**
Civil Engineering at USyd offers specialisations in structural, geotechnical, and transport engineering. The **Centre for Infrastructure Engineering and Safety** (CIES) conducts research on bridge design and earthquake resilience, with projects funded by the Australian Research Council (ARC) worth over $20 million since 2015. Students in the Bachelor of Engineering (Honours) (Civil) complete a mandatory 12-week industry placement, with partners including Arup, Aurecon, and Transport for NSW.

### **Computer Science & AI**
The **School of Computer Science** hosts the **Australian Artificial Intelligence Institute**, which was awarded $20 million in ARC funding in 2022 for research on trustworthy AI and machine learning. USyd’s computer science program offers a Master of Artificial Intelligence, launched in 2023, with coursework covering deep learning, natural language processing, and computer vision. The program’s employability rate is 92% within six months, with graduates joining Google, Atlassian, and Canva.

## **Business & Economics**

The **University of Sydney Business School** holds triple accreditation from AACSB, AMBA, and EQUIS—a distinction held by fewer than 1% of business schools globally. In QS 2024 subject rankings, **Accounting & Finance** placed 25th globally, **Business & Management Studies** ranked 35th, and **Economics & Econometrics** ranked 45th. The business school offers a Master of Commerce with 18 specialisations, including Business Analytics, Finance, and International Business. The **Discipline of Finance** is particularly strong: USyd finance research ranks 15th globally by publications in top-tier journals (Journal of Finance, Journal of Financial Economics) over 2018–2023, according to the UTD Top 100 Business School Research Rankings. The **Business School’s Career and Employer Relations Office** reports that 89% of Master of Commerce graduates secure full-time employment within three months of graduation, with median starting salaries of AUD $85,000 in 2023.

### **MBA Programs**
The Sydney MBA (Full-Time) is a 18-month program ranked 41st globally in the Financial Times Global MBA Ranking 2024. The program includes a two-week international study tour to Singapore or the United States, and a capstone consulting project with real clients. Average GMAT score for admitted students is 660, and 35% of MBA students are international, from 22 countries.

### **Executive Education**
The **Executive Education unit** offers short courses and micro-credentials in leadership, digital transformation, and sustainability. In 2023, over 3,000 professionals completed these programs, with corporate clients including Commonwealth Bank, Qantas, and the Australian government.

## **Arts, Humanities & Education**

The **Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences** at USyd is the largest humanities faculty in Australia, with over 10,000 students. In QS 2024 subject rankings, **Education & Training** placed 20th globally, **English Language & Literature** ranked 24th, **History** ranked 35th, and **Philosophy** ranked 30th. The **Sydney School of Education and Social Work** offers a Master of Teaching (Secondary) that leads to teacher registration in Australia, with a 96% employability rate for graduates. The **Department of English** houses the **Sydney Centre for Medieval and Early Modern Studies**, which has published over 200 books since 2010. For **Performing Arts**, USyd ranked 45th globally in QS 2024, with the **Sydney Conservatorium of Music** offering programs in classical performance, jazz, and composition. The Conservatorium hosts over 400 public performances annually and has produced alumni including composer Elena Kats-Chernin and conductor Simone Young.

### **Linguistics & Languages**
Linguistics at USyd ranked 28th globally in QS 2024. The **Department of Linguistics** offers a Master of Applied Linguistics with specialisations in TESOL, language testing, and discourse analysis. Research strengths include Australian Indigenous languages documentation, with projects funded by the ARC Discovery Program.

### **Archaeology & Anthropology**
Archaeology ranked 39th globally in QS 2024. The **Department of Archaeology** conducts field schools in Egypt, Greece, and the Pacific Islands. In 2023, USyd archaeologists discovered a 3,000-year-old burial site in Vanuatu, published in *Nature*.

## **Natural Sciences & Life Sciences**

USyd’s **Faculty of Science** is the largest in Australia, with over 6,000 students and 1,200 research staff. In QS 2024 subject rankings, **Veterinary Science** placed 16th globally, **Geography** ranked 30th, **Environmental Sciences** ranked 40th, **Geology** ranked 45th, and **Physics & Astronomy** ranked 50th. The **Sydney School of Veterinary Science** is the oldest veterinary school in Australia, established in 1910, and operates a teaching hospital that treats over 15,000 animals annually. The **School of Life and Environmental Sciences** manages the **Camperdown Campus Green**, a 10-hectare urban biodiversity research site. In the THE 2024 Life Sciences ranking, USyd placed 45th globally, driven by high citation impact in ecology and evolutionary biology. The **School of Physics** hosts the **Sydney Astrophotonic Instrumentation Laboratories**, which contributed to the design of the Giant Magellan Telescope, a $1 billion international project.

### **Marine Science**
Marine Science at USyd is housed within the **School of Geosciences**, with research stations at One Tree Island and the Sydney Institute of Marine Science. The program offers a Master of Marine Science and Management, with specialisations in coastal management and marine conservation. In 2023, USyd marine biologists published 150 papers on coral reef resilience, with 40% in top-quartile journals.

### **Mathematics & Statistics**
Mathematics ranked 51–100 globally in QS 2024. The **School of Mathematics and Statistics** offers a Master of Mathematical Sciences with streams in data science and financial mathematics. Research groups in pure mathematics have produced 30 PhD graduates per year since 2020, with placements at universities including Oxford and Princeton.

## FAQ

### Q1: What is the University of Sydney’s global ranking for Medicine in 2024?
The University of Sydney’s Medicine program ranks 27th globally in the QS World University Rankings by Subject 2024. This places it within the top 30 worldwide, with an academic reputation score of 88.4/100 and a research citation score of 91.2/100. The faculty also holds 12th place globally for Anatomy & Physiology and 18th for Pharmacy & Pharmacology, making health sciences one of the university’s strongest subject clusters.

### Q2: Does the University of Sydney offer scholarships for international students?
Yes, the University of Sydney offers over 400 scholarship programs for international students, with total funding exceeding AUD $80 million annually. The **Sydney International Student Award** provides a 20% tuition fee reduction for eligible undergraduate and postgraduate coursework students. The **Vice-Chancellor’s International Scholarships Scheme** awards up to AUD $40,000 per year for high-achieving students, with selection based on academic merit (minimum ATAR equivalent of 95 or GPA of 6.0/7.0). Approximately 15% of new international enrolments receive some form of scholarship.

### Q3: How long does it take to complete a Master’s degree at the University of Sydney?
Most Master’s programs at the University of Sydney require 1.5 to 2 years of full-time study. For example, the Master of Commerce (18 specialisations) is 1.5 years (72 credit points), while the Master of Data Science is 1.5 years, and the Master of Engineering is 2 years (96 credit points). Programs with a research component, such as the Master of Philosophy (MPhil), typically take 1.5 to 2 years. Accelerated pathways are available for students with relevant prior study, reducing duration by up to one semester.

